{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507316"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:52:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:52:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2620"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2620"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.61,0.02,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106939"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2620"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89425"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2089"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"8965"},{"type":"tags","id":"9718"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2913"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27071"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44945"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106939"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old male presents to his General Practice clinic with difficulty hearing, especially in crowded environments and with high pitched sounds. He describes tinnitus in both ears often late at night which is disrupting his sleep. He has no issues with balance. He has worked as a carpenter for his adult life. He denies previous head trauma but noted several ear infections as a child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn exam, he appears well and vital signs are within normal limits. On neurological assessment his gait was normal. His Weber\u0027s test is central and Rinne\u0027s test shows air conduction is better than bone conduction bilaterally. Other cranial nerve assessments were unremarkable and otoscopy was normal. He undergoes audiology assessment which shows decreased hearing, worst at 4000Hz which improved by 8000Hz bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Presbycusis","Noise-induced hearing loss","Wax build up","Chronic otitis media","Meniere\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests the differential diagnosis of hearing loss. Importantly, based on the cranial nerve eight findings this patient either has normal hearing or bilateral sensorineural hearing loss. Given they presented with hearing loss, it is the latter. This rules out \u003Cstrong\u003Ewax build up\u003C/strong\u003E (conductive deficit), as does normal otoscopy, as well \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic otitis media\u003C/strong\u003E as the cause. There is no associated vestibular pathology making \u003Cstrong\u003EMeniere\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E unlikely. The final two diagnosis are both very relevant differentials. \u003Cstrong\u003ENoise-induced hearing loss\u003C/strong\u003E (NIHL) is more likely given the history, the relative young age of the patient and the audiogram result being worst at 4000Hz where as in \u003Cstrong\u003Epresbycusis\u003C/strong\u003E it continues to decline as frequency increases. NIHL is postulated to be worst at 4000Hz as this is the resonant frequency of the ear canal/bony structures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Noise-induced hearing loss is worst at 4000Hz on audiogram.","Noise-induced hearing loss is a common occupational hazard, especially in professions with prolonged exposure to loud noises, such as carpentry."],"references":["Le TN, Straatman LV, Lea J, Westerberg B. Current insights in noise-induced hearing loss: a literature review of the underlying mechanism, pathophysiology, asymmetry, and management options. J Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2017 May 23;46(1):41. doi: 10.1186/s40463-017-0219-x. PMID: 28535812; PMCID: PMC5442866. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28535812/","Natarajan N, Batts S, Stankovic KM. Noise-Induced Hearing Loss. J Clin Med. 2023 Mar 17;12(6):2347. doi: 10.3390/jcm12062347. Erratum in: J Clin Med. 2024 Feb 07;13(4):944. doi: 10.3390/jcm13040944. PMID: 36983347; PMCID: PMC10059082. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36983347/","Metidieri MM, Rodrigues HF, Filho FJ, Ferraz DP, Neto AF, Torres S. Noise-Induced Hearing Loss (NIHL): literature review with a focus on occupational medicine. Int Arch Otorhinolaryngol. 2013 Apr;17(2):208-12. doi: 10.7162/S1809-97772013000200015. PMID: 25992015; PMCID: PMC4399645. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4399645/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89425"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2620"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89425"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T10:55:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T10:56:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2620"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106939"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\u